<div style=3D"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;">on 18 May 2016:<br>
<br>
Title: Cubic phases and cubosomes from ternary systems containing glycerol =
mono-oleate<br>
<br>
Speaker:<br>
<br>
Dr. Guruswamy Kumaraswamy<br>
Scientist<br>
Polymer and Advanced Materials Laboratory<br>
National Chemical Laboratory<br>
Dr. Homi Bhabha Road<br>
Pune 411008, India<br>
Phone &nbsp;&#43;91 20 2590 2182<br>
E-mail <a href=3D"mailto:g.kumaraswamy@ncl.res.in">g.kumaraswamy@ncl.res.in=
</a><br>
<br>
</div>
<div style=3D"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;"><font color=3D"black" f=
ace=3D"Calibri,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif" size=3D"3"><span dir=3D"ltr" sty=
le=3D"font-size: 12pt;"><font face=3D"Calibri,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif"><=
font face=3D"Calibri,Arial,Helvetica,sans-serif">Abstract:
 I will describe our recent work on ternary phases containing<br>
glycerol monooleate (GMO), water and polymers.&nbsp; GMO is a hydrophobic <=
br>
food-grade lipid that forms a variety of equilibrium phases.&nbsp; Of parti=
cular<br>
interest are the bicontinuous phases, since they can be used to encapsulate=
<br>
both hydrophilic and hydrophobic moieties.&nbsp; I will discuss our work on=
 <br>
cubosomes, viz. lipid nanoparticles with internal cubic phase structure and=
<br>
demonstrate how coating with a single polymer layer renders them as<br>
powerful theranostic entities.&nbsp; To overcome the limitations of burst r=
elease<br>
from such cubosomes, we explore the possibility of producing discontinuous<=
br>
cubic phase inverse structures using the same lipid-water system.&nbsp; We<=
br>
demonstrate that polar molecules that (i) have a compact molecular<br>
architecture and (ii) have attractive interactions with the lipid head grou=
p<br>
can induce discontinuous micellar cubic phases in the system at room<br>
temperature.&nbsp; This is unprecedented since it was previously believed t=
hat<br>
this could be achieved only by addition of apolar oils.&nbsp; Finally, I wi=
ll discuss<br>
an interesting application of cubosomes dispersions as low-splash effective=
<br>
delivery agents on hydrophobic surfaces.<br>
</font></font></span></font><br>
</div>
